{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504261","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504261"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:13:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:13:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2315"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2315","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2315"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.81,0.01,0.12,0.06,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2315"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"30551"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2315","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2315"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2315"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"16493"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"237"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"708"},{"type":"contributions","id":"713"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1259"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1453"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"30551","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/30551"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 80-year-old woman with a background of dementia is brought in by her daughter to the GP clinic. The patient has an ulcer above her right ankle, which was first noticed by the staff in the nursing home about seven days ago and it has been increasing in size ever since. When staff members tried to take a closer inspection, she was aggressive towards them and would shout and scream whenever they tried to inspect the lesion. Eliciting a history is difficult because of her dementia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, the ulcer is located above the right lateral malleolus. There are multiple yellow-brown hemosiderin staining surrounding the lower limbs which obscured the ulcer. However, the edges appear to be irregular and friable. Foot pulses are present bilaterally. Inspection of her lower limb showed bilateral pitting ankle oedema up to the proximal knee.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Four-layer compression bandage","Reassure and discharge","Refer for excisional biopsy","Initiate phosphodiesterase inhibitors (PDE inhibitors)","Advise her to immobilise for six weeks"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis lesion described above suggests a venous ulcer. This patient has behavioural and psychological symptoms of dementia and therefore further investigations and/or any invasive procedures would prove to be challenging and unhelpful. Any invasive interventions would require anaesthetics as well which would not be helpful in an 80-year-old elderly patient suffering from dementia. Conservative management for venous ulcers includes a \u003Cstrong\u003Efour\u003C/strong\u003E-\u003Cstrong\u003Elayer\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Ecompression\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Ebandage\u003C/strong\u003E. This works by applying controlled pressure to the surface veins which forces blood back into the deep vein system. This facilitates healing in active ulcers and prevents further ulcer recurrences. It is important to replace this compression bandage on a weekly basis. It is also critical that the clinician confirms that foot pulses are present before putting the lower extremity into compression.\u0026nbsp;\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is important to keep the ulcer under routine review with adequate pain relief. If the ulcer worsens or conservative management fails, this would warrant further investigation and management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnother differential diagnosis of venous ulcers is cutaneous malignancy. An excisional biopsy is required if this was a squamous cell carcinoma (SCC). If the venous ulcer was diagnosed but does not reduce in size by 50% in four weeks, a cutaneous malignancy should be suspected and an excisional biopsy is warranted. However, these lesions are usually slow-growing and appear on sun-exposed regions such as cheeks and lips. SCC may also erode or become nodular, and may have a friable surface that can bleed easily.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMobilising is useful in chronic venous insufficiency as it promotes calf muscle pump in pushing venous blood back up the legs. This contributes to improving wound healing and the prevention of future ulceration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPDE inhibitors are used in the management of peripheral arterial disease, not chronic venous insufficiency.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Compression bandaging provides appropriate care for most chronic venous ulcers."],"references":["Milic DJ, Zivic SS, Bogdanovic DC, et al. Risk factors related to the failure of venous leg ulcers to heal with compression treatment. J Vasc Surg 2009; 49:1242.","Simka M. Calf muscle pump impairment and delayed healing of venous leg ulcers: air plethysmographic findings. J Dermatol 2007; 34:537.","Heinen MM, van der Vleuten C, de Rooij MJ, et al. Physical activity and adherence to compression therapy in patients with venous leg ulcers. Arch Dermatol 2007; 143:1283.","Jull A, Slark J, Parsons J. Prescribed Exercise With Compression vs Compression Alone in Treating Patients With Venous Leg Ulcers: A Systematic Review and Meta-analysis. JAMA Dermatol 2018; 154:1304."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"16493"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2315"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"16493","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/16493"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2022-12-02T09:00:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2022-12-02T09:00:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2315"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"30551"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"21","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/21"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb5","name":"Vascular Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"237","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/237"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Venous ulcer","synonyms":[],"de